Implements Pass B ("type-append") of the stroke-expansion pipeline: given entries whose template already has argument-count expanded (Pass A upstream), it fills each entry's `%t` slot(s) by appending type-selector strokes, producing a chain of progressively-more-complete `TypedEntry` steps for arity-N generics (e.g. `Map`, `Map string`, `Map<string, number>`).

Behavioral core: a slot is either arity-0 (fills in one terminal step) or arity-N (stays non-terminal, accumulating space-joined bracketless type names via `render_type`, until enough args are appended, at which point the terminal step renders real brackets). Nested generics as generic args are explicitly unsupported — `expand_multi_slot`'s pool (`opts.generic_args`) is restricted to arity-0 types only, since multi-slot templates (typed params, several `%t` in one template) draw every slot from that same flat pool via `rec_multi`, which emits one `TypedEntry` per non-empty prefix of chosen pool types (partial fills are non-terminal, full fills terminal).

Two distinct single-slot strategies: normal append (`appended`) suffixes the entry's stroke with `f.suffix.join("/")` and keeps a separate non-terminal "base" entry (type-less skeleton) as the first output; fuse mode (`expand_fused`, triggered by `entry.source.flags.fuse()`) instead pops the construct's last stroke segment (the shape selector) and merges it via `crate::stroke::merge_strokes` into the *first* stroke of each filling's suffix, and drops the type-less base entirely — so fused constructs never emit a bare skeleton step. `merge_strokes` can fail (shared-key collision), which is the only error source in this file; that `Result` propagates through `expand_fused` → `expand_types_one` → `expand_types`.

Entries with zero `%t` slots pass through unchanged as a single terminal entry. Entries with exactly one slot use append-or-fuse; entries with 2+ slots always use `expand_multi_slot` regardless of fuse flag (fuse only applies to single-slot fusing).

Depends on sibling modules `fill.rs` (defines `Filling`, and the template/rendering helpers `fill_template`, `fillings`, `render_type`, `with_types`) and `types.rs` (`TypeDef`, `TypeOptions`) — any change to `Filling`'s shape or `fillings()`'s ordering changes what `appended`/`expand_fused`/`rec_multi` produce. `ExpandedEntry`/`TypedEntry` struct shapes live in the parent `expand` module (`super::{ExpandedEntry, TypedEntry}`); `typed()` here must stay in sync with `TypedEntry`'s fields (`stroke`, `template`, `terminal`, `one_liner`, `count`, `source`) — note `one_liner` is hardcoded `false` here, set elsewhere in the pipeline.

Public entry points: `expand_types_one(entry: &ExpandedEntry, opts: &TypeOptions) -> Result<Vec<TypedEntry>, ExpandError>` handles one entry; `expand_types(entries: &[ExpandedEntry], opts: &TypeOptions) -> Result<Vec<TypedEntry>, ExpandError>` maps it over a slice, short-circuiting on the first error.